<TITLE> Depression moves far away, level 3 alarm raised </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Aug 14 (bdnews24.com)  The land depression that was hovering over the Indian state of West Bengal and Bangladesh moved further to the northwest at around 6:00am Tuesday. The obvious depression is staying in the foothills of the Himalayas in West Bengal and areas close by. The met office said the depression would become weak to induce rainfalls. Monir Uddin, a weather official, told bdnews24.com the difference of wind force in the north Bay of Bengal is high due to the depression. The gusty wind may continue in the seaports. The maritime ports of Chttagong, Cox's Bazaar and Mongla have been told to raise local cautionary signal 3 again. The trawlers staying in the north Bay have been asked to stay close to the coast until further notice. bdnews24.com Cox's Bazar correspondent said due to accumulated clouds created by the depression, the Cox's Bazar beach and Bay of Bengal were wild on Monday but quiet until Tuesday morning. A trawler capsized in Cox's Bazar and Teknaf areas in the stormy wind Monday, leaving seven fishermen killed. Many men are still missing, the locals said. The bdnews24.com Patuakhali correspondent said tidal waters receded from Patuakhali town. The tide breached the embankment Monday and inundated the town and different shoals in Patuakhali. bdnews24.com/
